> Don't let the pungent aroma of ginger discourage you. It adds a peppery and
> slightly sweet flavor to a wide variety of Asian dishes. For this quick and
> easy stir-fry, our chefs put their own spin on a traditional Thai dish called
> Pad Krapow Moo by pairing ginger and mint.

Cook the rice: Bring 1 cup salted water to a boil in a small #pot. Once boiling,
add the @Basmati rice{1/2%cup}. Cover and reduce to a simmer for ~{15-20%minutes},
until al dente.

Wash and dry all produce. Trim and halve the @green beans{6%oz}. Peel and mince
the @ginger{1%thumb}. Mince or grate the @garlic{2%cloves}. Trim and cut the
@scallions{2%unit} into 1-inch pieces. Core, seed, and thinly slice the
@red bell pepper{1%unit}. Coarsely chop the @mint{1/4%oz} leaves.

Heat a large drizzle of @olive oil{4%tsp} in a large pan over high heat. Add
the green beans, bell pepper, and scallions. Cook, tossing, for
~{3-4%minutes}, until softened and starting to brown. Season with @salt{} and
@pepper{}. Remove from the pan and set aside.

Reduce the heat to medium and add another large drizzle of oil in the same pan.
Add the garlic and ginger. Cook, tossing, for ~{1-2%minutes}, until fragrant.

Increase the heat to medium-high and add the @ground pork{10%oz}. Cook, breaking
up the meat into pieces, for ~{3-5%minutes}, until browned. Toss in the veggies
along with the @soy sauce{6%tsp} and 1 Tablespoon @honey{1%jar}. Taste and
season with salt and pepper.

Finish and plate: Remove the pan from the heat and stir in half the mint. Fluff
the rice with a fork. Serve the Thai pork stir-fry on a bed of rice and garnish
with the remaining mint. Enjoy!